Caesar, influ- enced by his familiarity with Roman practice, may have gener- alized on insufficient data, or, in the interval between Caesar and 'rac-itus, conditions may have changed. Caesar's assertion, Bellum Gallicum 6. 21. 1; neque druides habent, qui rebus divinis praesint, neque sacrificiis student, in so far as it tends to minimize the functions of the priest in German life, is also at variance with the conditions portrayed by Tacitus, who, although he does not imply the existence of a hierarehy comparable with the Druids, assigns important prerogatives to the priest. The priest is the authorized instrument of divine punishment, presides over divination (chap. 10), has power to enforce silence in council (chap. 11).
